WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.960 --> 00:00:03.332
Professor Charles
Bailyn: Just in time for our

00:00:03.332 --> 00:00:05.568
last class, we get this in
yesterday's New York

00:00:05.568 --> 00:00:07.850
Times, and all over the rest
of the media.

00:00:07.850 --> 00:00:11.360
"New Planet Could Be
Earth-like."

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:13.763
You know, every time they get a
new planet, it's always

00:00:13.763 --> 00:00:15.900
Earth-like, but this one might
really be true.

00:00:15.900 --> 00:00:19.999
It was found by the standard
Doppler shift method,

00:00:19.999 --> 00:00:24.818
which you guys all remember,
and turns out to be the lowest

00:00:24.818 --> 00:00:28.821
mass planet that's been
discovered in that particular

00:00:28.821 --> 00:00:31.177
way.
And so, as a kind of final

00:00:31.177 --> 00:00:34.813
farewell calculation,
I thought we'd check the New

00:00:34.813 --> 00:00:39.477
York Times' numbers on this.
You can go back and read the

00:00:39.477 --> 00:00:44.482
article for yourself.
The information given there is

00:00:44.482 --> 00:00:49.050
that the orbital period is about
13 days.

00:00:49.050 --> 00:00:54.500
The distance between the planet
and its star – that's the

00:00:54.500 --> 00:00:59.200
semi-major axis – is given as
7 million miles.

00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:01.651
These are, of course,
not the world's best set of

00:01:01.651 --> 00:01:04.586
units.
The distance to the system is

00:01:04.586 --> 00:01:08.959
20 light-years.
That's really close.

00:01:08.959 --> 00:01:10.663
Somebody's quoted in the
article as saying,

00:01:10.663 --> 00:01:15.269
you know, we could go there.
Not so much.

00:01:15.269 --> 00:01:18.887
And I looked up the apparent
magnitude of this star,

00:01:18.887 --> 00:01:21.370
which turns out to be about
10.5.

00:01:21.370 --> 00:01:25.580
And so, what can we do with
information of this kind?

00:01:25.580 --> 00:01:29.012
Well, let's first put this into
some kind of sane set of units,

00:01:29.012 --> 00:01:33.610
here.
Thirteen days is--let's see.

00:01:33.610 --> 00:01:39.580
Three days is--3.5 days would
be 1% of a year.

00:01:39.580 --> 00:01:42.960
So, this is,
like, 3 x 10^(-2) of a year.

00:01:42.960 --> 00:01:51.311
Seven million miles.
That's something like 10

00:01:51.311 --> 00:01:55.230
million kilometers,
10^(7) kilometers,

00:01:55.230 --> 00:02:00.527
which is 10^(10) meters.
So, that's something like 7 x

00:02:00.527 --> 00:02:04.281
10^(-2) Astronomical Units.
And you know right away what to

00:02:04.281 --> 00:02:05.457
do with that,
or, at least,

00:02:05.457 --> 00:02:08.080
you will if you go back in your
notes for a few months.

00:02:08.080 --> 00:02:11.771
This is in good units to use
a^(3) = P^(2)

00:02:11.771 --> 00:02:13.479
M.
M, then,

00:02:13.479 --> 00:02:16.879
shows up in solar masses.
So let's figure out the mass of

00:02:16.879 --> 00:02:24.102
this star.
Let's see, (7 x 10^(-2))^(3) /

00:02:24.102 --> 00:02:29.993
(3 x 10^(-2))^(2).
That'll be the mass in solar

00:02:29.993 --> 00:02:33.546
masses.
7 x 7 = 50, times 7 is 350,

00:02:33.546 --> 00:02:39.793
times 10^(-6) over 10 x 10^(-4)
[(350 x 10^(-8)) / (10 x

00:02:39.793 --> 00:02:46.080
10^(-4))].
That's 35 x 10^(-2).

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:50.850
.35, which is 1/3.
Okay?

00:02:50.850 --> 00:02:55.169
So, this star is 1/3 of the
mass of Sun--perfectly

00:02:55.169 --> 00:02:58.430
respectable mass for a star to
be.

00:02:58.430 --> 00:03:04.010
And then--let's see.
Let's do something else.

00:03:04.010 --> 00:03:06.920
It's 20 light-years away.

00:03:10.919 --> 00:03:14.716
Twenty light years,
that's something like 6

00:03:14.716 --> 00:03:17.058
parsecs.
So, it's really nearby,

00:03:17.058 --> 00:03:19.815
as these things go.
Not that you would want to take

00:03:19.815 --> 00:03:22.583
a spaceship and go there or
anything, but it is one of the

00:03:22.583 --> 00:03:25.689
closer stars.
And then, we can do this thing.

00:03:25.689 --> 00:03:30.000
We can figure out the absolute
magnitude of this star.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.490
I've written down the apparent
magnitude.

00:03:33.490 --> 00:03:36.190
So, that's that equation.
Let's see.

00:03:36.190 --> 00:03:44.634
5 log (6/10).
Let's call that 2 x 3 x

00:03:44.634 --> 00:03:51.199
10^(-1), yeah?
That's 6/10 - five.

00:03:51.199 --> 00:03:53.104
And then, you know,
this thing about logs,

00:03:53.104 --> 00:03:55.705
if you multiply them inside the
bracket, you can add them

00:03:55.705 --> 00:03:59.818
outside the bracket.
So, this is log of 2,

00:03:59.818 --> 00:04:04.960
plus log of 3,
plus log of 10^(-1).

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:07.763
Log of 10^(-1) is -1,
and the other two,

00:04:07.763 --> 00:04:10.940
I happen to know.
The log of 2 is .3.

00:04:10.940 --> 00:04:19.600
The log of 3 is .5.
Minus one, that's 5 x -.2 = -1.

00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:26.100
And so, 10.5 minus the absolute
magnitude would be -1.

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:27.920
Let's see.
How's this going to work?

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:31.130
This has to go over there.
That has to come over here.

00:04:31.130 --> 00:04:37.273
Absolute magnitude, 11.5.
Now, you may remember that the

00:04:37.273 --> 00:04:41.350
Sun has a magnitude--an absolute
magnitude of around 5.

00:04:41.350 --> 00:04:44.480
So, this is much,
much fainter than the Sun.

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:46.679
That's good,
because it's less massive than

00:04:46.679 --> 00:04:49.560
the Sun, and low mass stars get
faint really quickly.

00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:53.145
How much fainter?
Well, we know how to do that,

00:04:53.145 --> 00:04:53.620
right?

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.973
Let's see, that looks--in the
easiest format,

00:05:00.973 --> 00:05:04.946
it looks like this:
M_star -

00:05:04.946 --> 00:05:09.371
M_sun =
b_star /

00:05:09.371 --> 00:05:13.584
b_sun.
This a minus sign out here in

00:05:13.584 --> 00:05:15.199
front?
Yes.

00:05:15.199 --> 00:05:26.484
So, that's 10^(-2/5 (11.5 -
5)), which is equal to

00:05:26.484 --> 00:05:31.931
10^((-2/5)(6.5)).
All right, what are we going to

00:05:31.931 --> 00:05:36.480
do about that?
6.5 over – 65/5 = 13.

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:48.320
So, this is 10^(-1.3 x 2).
2.6.

00:05:48.320 --> 00:05:50.818
You could work it out.
And that, in turn,

00:05:50.818 --> 00:05:54.613
is equal to--remember,
this is b_star

00:05:54.613 --> 00:05:58.336
/ b_sun,
brightness of the star over

00:05:58.336 --> 00:06:04.471
brightness of the Sun.
That's 10^(0.4) x 10^(-3);

00:06:04.471 --> 00:06:12.388
3+; 3 + .4; - 2.6 and that's
– oh, I don't know,

00:06:12.388 --> 00:06:18.689
what, 2.5 at a guess,
times 10^(-3).

00:06:18.689 --> 00:06:21.290
A tiny fraction of the
brightness of the Sun.

00:06:21.290 --> 00:06:23.879
Less than 1% as bright as the
Sun.

00:06:23.879 --> 00:06:26.270
And this is the importance of
the discovery.

00:06:26.270 --> 00:06:32.370
Because it's in a 13-day orbit.
It's really quite close to the

00:06:32.370 --> 00:06:34.590
star.
We figured out how close.

00:06:34.590 --> 00:06:38.788
It's 7%.
The distance of the Earth to

00:06:38.788 --> 00:06:42.750
the Sun is this planet from its
star.

00:06:42.750 --> 00:06:45.019
But the star is much fainter
too.

00:06:45.019 --> 00:06:48.460
And so, if you do the little
calculation, which is quite

00:06:48.460 --> 00:06:52.212
straightforward to do – we
won't do it here – of how much

00:06:52.212 --> 00:06:55.089
energy this planet receives from
its star,

00:06:55.089 --> 00:06:58.879
compared to the amount of
energy that the Earth receives

00:06:58.879 --> 00:07:01.911
from the Sun,
you get almost exactly the same

00:07:01.911 --> 00:07:04.655
answer.
So, here is a planet whose

00:07:04.655 --> 00:07:09.162
surface temperature is likely to
be quite similar to that of

00:07:09.162 --> 00:07:11.753
Earth.
Here is a planet where liquid

00:07:11.753 --> 00:07:14.580
water could exist.
Now, we don't actually know

00:07:14.580 --> 00:07:17.449
that much about this planet
except for its mass.

00:07:17.449 --> 00:07:20.316
It's five times the mass of the
Sun--sorry, five times the mass

00:07:20.316 --> 00:07:22.661
of the Earth.
That could be either a big

00:07:22.661 --> 00:07:26.091
Earth or a small Neptune,
and those are quite different

00:07:26.091 --> 00:07:28.398
objects.
And we don't really know what

00:07:28.398 --> 00:07:30.839
category, from that point of
view, it's in.

00:07:30.839 --> 00:07:33.300
It seems unlikely that it would
be a big Earth,

00:07:33.300 --> 00:07:35.120
because this is a low-mass
star.

00:07:35.120 --> 00:07:37.920
It's also, as it turns out,
a low-metallicity star.

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:42.594
So, it's got only 1/3 the stuff
of the Sun, and it's got less

00:07:42.594 --> 00:07:46.879
than 1/2 the frequency of heavy
materials as the Sun.

00:07:46.879 --> 00:07:50.292
And so, it's hard to imagine it
could build up a rocky planet

00:07:50.292 --> 00:07:53.420
five times bigger than the
Earth, but you never know.

00:07:53.420 --> 00:07:57.297
Stranger things than that have
happened, and will probably

00:07:57.297 --> 00:07:59.269
happen again,
in astronomy.

00:07:59.269 --> 00:08:01.500
So, you don't know what will
happen with this one.

00:08:01.500 --> 00:08:03.956
There's rumors going around,
I should say,

00:08:03.956 --> 00:08:07.312
that there are even more
entertaining planets going to be

00:08:07.312 --> 00:08:11.069
announced in the next few weeks,
so, keep your eye on the

00:08:11.069 --> 00:08:13.838
newspapers.
There may, in fact,

00:08:13.838 --> 00:08:17.391
be more to come.
Okay, so that's the last

00:08:17.391 --> 00:08:20.605
calculation, here.
You just never know when these

00:08:20.605 --> 00:08:22.880
things will show up in the
newspaper.

00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:25.004
Okay.
What we're going to do on

00:08:25.004 --> 00:08:27.875
Monday and Tuesday,
we're going to do this double

00:08:27.875 --> 00:08:30.440
strength section--sorry?
Monday and Wednesday.

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:32.195
Thank you.
We decided not to do the

00:08:32.195 --> 00:08:34.210
Tuesday one.
We've got you guys all

00:08:34.210 --> 00:08:36.004
sectioned.
I think there was an email

00:08:36.004 --> 00:08:38.110
yesterday, which told you what
section you're in.

00:08:38.110 --> 00:08:39.953
If you have any problems with
that, you know,

00:08:39.953 --> 00:08:41.629
make sure we know about it in
advance.

00:08:41.629 --> 00:08:44.911
And later, well,
probably Saturday,

00:08:44.911 --> 00:08:49.639
or so, I will post three pages
of instructions.

00:08:49.639 --> 00:08:52.412
You don't have to read them
particularly carefully,

00:08:52.412 --> 00:08:55.462
but I would like you to
download them and print them and

00:08:55.462 --> 00:08:57.679
to bring them with you to the
class.

00:08:57.679 --> 00:09:01.050
Let me take you through the
first page of this.

00:09:01.050 --> 00:09:04.879
Here we go.
Cosmology: The Game.

00:09:04.879 --> 00:09:08.059
And let me just take you
through the sequence of play,

00:09:08.059 --> 00:09:10.759
so you know approximately what
will happen.

00:09:10.759 --> 00:09:13.370
So, at the start of the game,
everybody gets a role.

00:09:13.370 --> 00:09:17.429
You can be a junior or a senior
scientist at one of several

00:09:17.429 --> 00:09:19.950
competing scientific
institutions,

00:09:19.950 --> 00:09:23.046
or a member of the review
committee that decides which

00:09:23.046 --> 00:09:25.231
projects to do.
Each of the competing

00:09:25.231 --> 00:09:28.580
institution then proposes a
project and a funding request.

00:09:28.580 --> 00:09:31.480
The senior scientist has to
present the case.

00:09:31.480 --> 00:09:34.720
The review committee then gets
to decide.

00:09:34.720 --> 00:09:36.650
And so, you can't do all of
them.

00:09:36.650 --> 00:09:39.389
You can only do some of them.
So, the review committee

00:09:39.389 --> 00:09:42.563
decides what projects to approve
and they give either partial or

00:09:42.563 --> 00:09:45.860
a full funding,
and then, they report why they

00:09:45.860 --> 00:09:48.649
have made the decisions they
make.

00:09:48.649 --> 00:09:53.835
And then, we tell you what the
results of that scientific

00:09:53.835 --> 00:09:56.059
exploration is.
So, you know,

00:09:56.059 --> 00:09:59.159
you go out and you try and find
more supernovae and we tell you

00:09:59.159 --> 00:10:02.253
that--I don't know what happens.
Magically, all the supernovae

00:10:02.253 --> 00:10:03.921
have disappeared,
or they're all way,

00:10:03.921 --> 00:10:06.052
way, way too bright,
or whatever it is that the

00:10:06.052 --> 00:10:09.259
answer turns out to be.
And then, you know a little bit

00:10:09.259 --> 00:10:11.708
more about the Universe.
At that point,

00:10:11.708 --> 00:10:14.692
the review committee,
which is made up of aging

00:10:14.692 --> 00:10:18.042
pundits, all die off.
The senior scientists are

00:10:18.042 --> 00:10:20.480
promoted to the review
committee.

00:10:20.480 --> 00:10:23.481
The junior scientists are
promoted to senior scientists,

00:10:23.481 --> 00:10:26.536
and the review committee are
reborn as junior scientists,

00:10:26.536 --> 00:10:29.067
or something like that.
And so, we sort of cycle

00:10:29.067 --> 00:10:31.186
through all the roles.
And you keep going through

00:10:31.186 --> 00:10:33.611
these cycles until you figure
out what the dark matter and

00:10:33.611 --> 00:10:36.379
what the dark energy is.
And then, at the end,

00:10:36.379 --> 00:10:40.545
we will sort of debrief,
and decide what the key moment

00:10:40.545 --> 00:10:44.248
of discovery was,
and award a suitable simulation

00:10:44.248 --> 00:10:49.302
of the Nobel Prize.
It was M&amp;Ms last year,

00:10:49.302 --> 00:10:53.009
but we'll see.
So, that's approximately what's

00:10:53.009 --> 00:10:55.621
going to happen.
And the key thing is what kind

00:10:55.621 --> 00:10:58.943
of projects can you propose?
And the other two pages of this

00:10:58.943 --> 00:11:02.396
handout are going to be a list
of potential projects that you

00:11:02.396 --> 00:11:05.025
can propose.
You can also propose anything

00:11:05.025 --> 00:11:08.129
else you can think of,
and we will invent results on

00:11:08.129 --> 00:11:11.781
the spot for any other kinds of
projects that get approved as

00:11:11.781 --> 00:11:13.861
well.
But I figured it would be a

00:11:13.861 --> 00:11:16.367
good idea for you to have,
at least, a range of

00:11:16.367 --> 00:11:19.201
possibilities of things you
might consider proposing,

00:11:19.201 --> 00:11:22.257
and why.
So, that will be posted on

00:11:22.257 --> 00:11:24.723
Saturday.
My experience is that in just

00:11:24.723 --> 00:11:26.987
under two hours,
you can figure out all the

00:11:26.987 --> 00:11:29.789
secrets of the Universe in this
particular--well,

00:11:29.789 --> 00:11:32.491
of a Universe that I design,
which is, you know,

00:11:32.491 --> 00:11:34.330
not as sophisticated,
perhaps,

00:11:34.330 --> 00:11:36.990
as the real Universe will turn
out to be.

00:11:36.990 --> 00:11:41.290
Okay, procedural questions on
any of that?

00:11:41.290 --> 00:11:43.280
Yes?
Student: So,

00:11:43.280 --> 00:11:45.967
the Universe that we're looking
at isn't going to be like the

00:11:45.967 --> 00:11:48.062
actual Universe as an exercise?
Professor Charles

00:11:48.062 --> 00:11:49.817
Bailyn: Who knows?
Since I don't know what the

00:11:49.817 --> 00:11:51.728
actual Universe is,
it would be a little hard to

00:11:51.728 --> 00:11:53.639
give you the actual Universe as
an exercise.

00:11:53.639 --> 00:11:57.030
What I have done is I have
invented a Universe,

00:11:57.030 --> 00:12:00.495
which is consistent with
everything we know now,

00:12:00.495 --> 00:12:03.960
and has many more answers than
we know now.

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:05.875
I would be very,
very fortunate,

00:12:05.875 --> 00:12:09.397
indeed, if that turned out to
have anything to do with the

00:12:09.397 --> 00:12:13.504
real Universe.
So, I wish it were true that I

00:12:13.504 --> 00:12:18.080
had those kinds of powers.
But it's possible.

00:12:18.080 --> 00:12:23.470
That's the key.
Other questions?

